entitled to public funding in relation to campaign support.</td><td class="d" id="d_162223"># Equal<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /># Proportional to votes received<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /></td><td>For both presidential and legislative elections, 50% is distributed equally among participating parties. The remaining half is distributed between constituencies and then to parties proportional to votes gained (Presidential) or half equal, half proportional to votes gained (legislative).</td><td class="d" id="d_218686"># Campaign spending<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /># Ongoing party activities<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /></td><td>Aside from receiving public funding for both purposes, campaign spending and ongoing activities, parties also receive public funding for printing their own ballot papers. Of the funding for ongoing activities, parties should devote at least 20% to training and research activities, and 30% of the latter for that type of activities but targeted to audiences less than 30 years</td><td class="d" id="d_219159">Yes</td><td>Parties have free access to media (radio and TV) for campaign purposes in  primary and general elections, but are banned from buying additional time.</td><td class="d" id="d_162843"># Equal<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /># Share of votes in preceding election<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /></td><td>Only parties that nominate candidates are eligible for free media access. Of the time available, 50% is allocated equally, and the rest according to the number of votes obtained in the previous election.</td><td class="d" id="d_151278">No</td><td>Candidates can only have access through the free
