new parties, formed after an election, having become legally registered</td><td class="d" id="d_162305"># Equal<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /># Proportional to votes received<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /></td><td>30% of the public funding are allocated on an equal basis among all parties, and  70% according to the share of votes obtained in the latest election for the Chamber of  Deputies.</td><td class="d" id="d_160881"># Campaign spending<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /># Ongoing party activities<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /># Intra-party institution<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /></td><td>Regular funding is for ongoing activities, on election years parties receive additional funding for campaign expenses. Of the funds parties receive for ongoing activities, at least 2% should be devoted to political education and training activities; political and socio-economic research, and publications; and another 2% to training, promotion and development of women leadership.</td><td class="d" id="d_219130">Yes</td><td>Political parties are granted free permanent access to radio and TV. Political parties are not allowed to buy airtime, directly or indirectly.</td><td class="d" id="d_162847"># Equal<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /># Share of votes in preceding election<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /></td><td>30% of the free time is allocated on an equal basis among all parties, and 70% according to the share of votes obtained in the latest election for the Chamber of Deputies.</td><td class="d" id="d_160084">No</td><td>Only to political parties</td><td class="d" id="d_162442"># Tax relief<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /># Free or subsidised postage cost<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /></td><td>Free postage and use of telegraphic facilities, as well as tax exemptions. </td><td class="d" id="d_161152">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_162615">Yes, funds earmarked for gender activities</td><td>Each party has to devote 2% of their yearly regular public funding to the training, promotion and development of women leadership.</td><td class="d" id="d_161071">Yes</td><td>Vote buying is subject to a fine and imprisonment from six months to three years.</td><td class="d" id="d_184609">Yes</td><td>Public officers are obliged to impartially allocate public resources  that are under their responsibility.</td><td class="d" id="d_218616">Yes</td><td>There are specific spending limits for each public office</td><td class="d" id="d_161171">Limit varies for each federal public office.</td><td>New formulas to determine the limits were introduced in 2008, after the latest general election. For the presidential and senatorial races scheduled in July 2012, new limits will be established by the end of 2011. The limit for the presidential race will be equal to 20% of the public funding allocated to all political parties for campaign expenses. </td><td class="d" id="d_218617">Yes</td><td>There are specific spending limits for each public office.</td><td class="d" id="d_218618">Limit varies for each federal public office, see source.</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_219133">Yes</td><td>During non election periods, political parties should submit an annual report and quarterly preliminary reports. During election periods, reports are to be filed every month.</td><td class="d" id="d_163009">Yes</td><td>During election periods, parties have to submit a report on pre-campaign expenses for each campaign, as well as one preliminary and one final expenses report.</td><td class="d" id="d_215826">Yes</td><td>Candidates must submit campaign reports disclosing campaign financing and expenses.</td><td class="d" id="d_215840">Yes</td><td>All financial reports submitted by political parties are regarded as public information, and as such should be publicly available.</td><td class="d" id="d_151942">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_215839">EMB</td><td>The National Electoral 