d" id="d_146225">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_150643">No data</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_146216">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_146222">Not applicable</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_161386">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_164038">TTD 50,000  [I$ 14,000] (Parliamentary election); TTD 25,000 [I$ 6,900] (Municipal Council or the Tobago House of Assembly election).</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_147263">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_147264">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_133854">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_163252">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_133858">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_133859">EMB</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_150644">No data</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_150645">No data</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_163720"># Fines<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /># Prison<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /></td><td></td></tr><tr class="even" ><td>United States</td><td translate='no'>US</td><td class="d" id="d_218261">Yes</td><td>Both direct and indirect donations of cash or other things of value are banned, as well as promising or implying donations.</td><td class="d" id="d_218262">Yes</td><td>Both direct and indirect donations of cash or other things of value are banned, as well as promising or implying donations.</td><td class="d" id="d_218263">Yes</td><td>Corporations and labor organizations may however establish Political Action Committees (PACs) where they can raise voluntary contributions from a restricted class of individuals and use those funds to support federal candidates and political committees.</td><td class="d" id="d_157242">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_218264">Yes</td><td>Donations, personal services and material, supplies or equipment cannot be donated by a person or company that has entered a contract with a government department or agency.</td><td class="d" id="d_218265">Yes</td><td>Donations, personal services and material, supplies or equipment cannot be donated by a person or company that has entered a contract with a government department or agency.</td><td class="d" id="d_218267">Yes</td><td>It is unlawful for labor organizations to make a contribution or expenditure in connection with any election to any political office.</td><td class="d" id="d_218255">Yes</td><td>It is unlawful for labor organizations to make a contribution or expenditure in connection with any election to any political office.</td><td class="d" id="d_218257">No, but specific limit</td><td>If an anonymous cash contribution over $50 is received, the amount must be used for some purpose unrelated to federal elections.</td><td class="d" id="d_218258">No, but specific limit</td><td>If an anonymous cash contribution over $50 is received, the amount must be used for some purpose unrelated to federal elections.</td><td class="d" id="d_218259">Yes</td><td>State resources cannot be used to finance, directly  or indirectly, any activity influencing the outcome of any election to Federal office.</td><td class="d" id="d_218260">Yes</td><td>There is a ban on donations over USD 100 [I$ 100] in cash, on donations from a national bank and on donations in the name of another.</td><td class="d" id="d_218268">Yes</td><td>See current limits at: http://www.fec.gov/ans/answers_general.shtml#How_much_can_I_contribute</td><td class="d" id="d_218269">There are different limits depending on the type of the contributor.</td><td>There are different limits depending on who contributes. See table at: http://www.fec.gov/ans/answers_general.shtml#How_much_can_I_contribute</td><td class="d" id="d_218270">Regular limit applies</td><td>The existing limits for donations to national party committees are per calender year. </td><td class="d" id="d_157267">Not applicable</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_218271">Yes</td><td>There are different limits depending on who contributes. See table at: http://www.fec.gov/ans/answers_general.shtml#How_much_can_I_contribute</td><td class="d" id="d_218273">There are different limits depending on who the contributor is.</td><td>There are different limits depending on who contributes. See table at: http://www.fec.gov/ans/answers_general.shtml#How_much_can_I_contribute</td><td class="d" id="d_218274">Yes, in relation to campaigns</td><td>Public funding is only provided to the party convention committees and candidates. Presidential candidates who accept the public funding must limit spending to the amount of the grant. There are public grants available for candidates in both the primary and general elections.</td><td class="d" id="d_218275"># Share of votes in previous election<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /># Share of votes in next election<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /># Limiting campaign spending<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /></td><td>Major parties are entitled to public funding, minor parties may be eligible if they fulfill certain criteria.</td><td class="d" id="d_164795">Equal</td><td>Public funding is distributed equally between eligble major parties in the general election. Minor parties eligible for public funding recieves an amount which bears the same ratio to the major parties public funding as the number of popular votes recieved  in the previous presidential election does to the average number of popular votes recieved by the major parties. </td><td class="d" id="d_218277">Presidential nominating convention</td><td>Funding is ear marked to be used for Presidential nominating conventions.</td><td class="d" id="d_157286">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_157287">Not applicable</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_159451">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_162494">Tax relief</td><td>So called 527s (following section 527 of the Internal Revenue Code) are political organizations exempted from tax. They may not coordinate their activities with a candidate or a party. </td><td class="d" id="d_157415">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_157300">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_157301">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_159449">Yes</td><td>Federal employees face limits to their involvement in election campaigns</td><td class="d" id="d_172018">Yes</td><td>Parties are subject to limits in relation to expenditure made in coordination with candidates (presidential and for federal office). However, there are no such limits for expenditure made without such coordination (independent spending).</td><td class="d" id="d_170918">The limit for coordinated expenditure is an amount equal to 2 cents multiplied by the voting age population of the United States.</td><td>However, these limits do not apply for expenditure made without such coordination (independent spending)</td><td class="d" id="d_172019">No</td><td>The expenditure limits is only applicable to candidates (presidential and for federal office) who accept public funding in the general election. Candidates who accept public funding must limit spending to the amount of the grant.</td><td class="d" id="d_157367">Not applicable</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_162970">Yes</td><td>Candidate committees, party committees and PACs are required to file periodic reports disclosing the money they raise and spend.</td><td class="d" id="d_164160">Yes</td><td>Candidate committees, party committees and PACs are required to file periodic reports disclosing the money they raise and spend. Candidates must identify, for example, all PACs and party committees that give them contributions, and they must identify individuals who give them more than $200 [I$ 200] in an election cycle. Additionally, they must disclose expenditures exceeding $200 [I$ 200] per election cycle to any individual or vendor.</td><td class="d" id="d_163190">Yes</td><td>Candidate committees, party committees and PACs are required to file periodic reports disclosing the money they raise and spend.</td><td class="d" id="d_157390">Yes</td><td>The reports are available at www.fec.gov</td><td class="d" id="d_163854">Sometimes</td><td>Reports must identify all PACs and party committees that give them contributions, and they must identify individuals who give them more than $200 [I$ 200] in an election cycle.</td><td class="d" id="d_218278">EMB</td><td>Federal Election Commission</td><td class="d" id="d_159456"># Yes, EMB<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /># Yes, ministry<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /></td><td>The Federal Election Commission has exclusive jurisdiction over the civil enforcement of the federal campaign finance law, while the Department of Justice prosecutes criminal violations. </td><td class="d" id="d_165096">Other</td><td>If the FEC determines that there is probable cause to believe that a violation has/will occur it may refer the case to the Attorney General. </td><td class="d" id="d_157546"># Fines<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /># Prison<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /># Forfeiture<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /></td><td></td></tr><tr class="odd" ><td>Uruguay</td><td translate='no'>UY</td><td class="d" id="d_152820">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_152821">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_219178">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_164446">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_160646">Yes</td><td>The ban applies to donations [from companies providing public service ] exceeding 10,000 inflation indexed units (these are units whose value changes as the index to which they are indexed changes, in this case inflation) per year.</td><td class="d" id="d_161344">Yes</td><td>Ban applies to contributions from corporations with contracts for the provision of public services that exceeds 10,000 IU per year.</td><td class="d" id="d_152828">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_152829">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_162679">No, but specific limit</td><td>Anonymous contributions may not exceed 4,000 Indexed Units and under no circumstances can anonymous donations exceed 15% of the political parties reported incomes in a year. </td><td class="d" id="d_163558">No, but specific limit</td><td>Donations below 4,000 UI are allowed. Anonymous donations can under no circumstances exceed 15% of the reported income during a year.</td><td class="d" id="d_164650">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_152834">Yes</td><td>Contributions by party foundations, criminal or illicit organizations, those imposed unilaterally by higher rank officers of any given institution or corporation, or from non state public institutions are also banned. </td><td class="d" id="d_152835">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_163760">Annual limit is UI 300,000 [I$ 17,000] (10,000 [I$ 580] for corporations with public service provision contracts)</td><td>Contributions from party representatives and elected officers are also limited yearly to 900,000 UI.</td><td class="d" id="d_162842">Regular limit applies</td><td>No special limits for election campaigns, annual limits apply.</td><td class="d" id="d_161882">Not applicable</td><td>Contributions from party representatives and elected officers are also limited yearly to 900,000 UI.</td><td class="d" id="d_152841">Yes</td><td>Yearly limits are also applicable to contributions to candidates. </td><td class="d" id="d_163801">Limit is 300,000 UI [I$ 17,000] yearly, 10,000 UI [I$ 580] for corporations with public service provision contracts.</td><td>Contributions from party representatives and elected officers are also limited yearly to 900,000 UI.</td><td class="d" id="d_208018">Yes, both regularly provided funding and in relation to campaigns</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_219158">Representation in elected body</td><td>Obtaining votes in the national election or in the municipal election and having presented the sworn statement of campaign expenses in proper time and form as per Law No. 18,485. In order to obtain permanent 
financing one must have legislative representation.</td><td class="d" id="d_162345">Flat rate by votes received</td><td>For campaign expenses, parties receive a flat rate of 87 indexed units per each valid vote obtained in the previous presidential election. </td><td class="d" id="d_164813">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_219166">Yes</td><td>Free access is granted for 50 days in case of general elections, and for 40 days in case of primaries. </td><td class="d" id="d_152849">Equal</td><td>All parties that obtained at least 3% of the votes casted in the open primaries are entitled to two minutes of free media access. </td><td class="d" id="d_160163">Yes</td><td>Only to presidential candidates from political parties with representation in Parliament (5 minutes at the beginning and 15 minutes at the end of the campaign period, and 2 minutes throughout the campaign period). </td><td class="d" id="d_162495">Tax relief</td><td>Assets and properties acquired by parties with public funding and devoted to party activities are tax exempted. 
 Their bank accounts are also tax exempted. </td><td class="d" id="d_162887">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_162888">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_153023">Yes</td><td>Vote buying is regarded as an electoral offence. </td><td class="d" id="d_153024">Yes</td><td>Involvement of public officers in political propaganda activities during labor days and hours is regarded as an ilicit activity. </td><td class="d" id="d_162895">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_161458">Not applicable</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_162896">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_161459">Not applicable</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_162971">Yes</td><td>Annually</td><td class="d" id="d_163032">Yes</td><td>Preliminary financial reports before the elections and one final after.</td><td class="d" id="d_163403">Yes</td><td>Lists of candidates have to submit preliminary and final financial reports</td><td class="d" id="d_163253">Yes</td><td>Financial reports submitted to the EMB are regarded as public and can be inspected by anyone interested without any restriction. Reports shall be posted in the web site of the EMB and published in the official gazette.</td><td class="d" id="d_153034">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_153035">EMB</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_160284">Yes, EMB</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_153037">None</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_153038"># Fines<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /># Other<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /></td><td>Corporations with contracts for the provision of public services could lose the franchise, and those with contracts for the development of public infrastructure could lose the possibility to make a bid in any future tender. </td></tr><tr class="even" ><td>Venezuela</td><td translate='no'>VE</td><td class="d" id="d_154623">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_154624">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_154625">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_163100">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_154628">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_154629">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_163101">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_163102">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_162680">Yes</td><td>Contributions and donations made through banking deposits or transfers that makes it difficult or impossible to identify the donor are also prohibited. </td><td class="d" id="d_163560">Yes</td><td>Contributions and donations made through banking deposits or transfers that makes it difficult or impossible to identify the donor are  prohibited.</td><td class="d" id="d_154636">Yes</td><td>It is established as an obligation of the Political parties not to accept donations or contributions from public entities </td><td class="d" id="d_163430">Yes</td><td>Resources of illicit origin or with private funds not declared to the EMB and the National Tax Office must not be used for campaigns.</td><td class="d" id="d_163103">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_161952">Not applicable</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_163104">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_161953">Not applicable</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_163105">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_161954">Not applicable</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_219084">No</td><td>However, public funding of electoral campaigns is technically allowed through a court decision in 2008.</td><td class="d" id="d_161955">Not applicable</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_161956">Not applicable</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_161957">Not applicable</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_218996">No</td><td>The law allows but does not oblige the Electoral Commission to finance advertising for parties.</td><td class="d" id="d_218628">No data</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_218629">Yes</td><td> The Supreme Justice Court ruled in 2008 that the constitutional mandate on parties financing does not prohibit public financing of campaigns. On this basis, the EMB issued a regulation that provided free media access for the referendum held that year.  It is uncertain if free media access will be granted in upcoming elections.</td><td class="d" id="d_163110">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_162840">Not applicable</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_163111">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_164925">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_154666">Yes</td><td>There is a series of prohibitions for public officers under the assumption that they are under the service of the state, and not of any Political organization. For instance, they cannot perform their duties in accordance with their political preferences or in favor or against any political organization, to conduct propaganda activities in their working spaces, or make use of any public facility for political purposes. </td><td class="d" id="d_164966">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_161959">Not applicable</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_164995">No</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_161960">Not applicable</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_219015">Yes</td><td>Parties are required to report on their finances through the an automatic system on the National Electoral Council website within 90 days of the end of the calendar year.</td><td class="d" id="d_163029">Yes</td><td>Monthly preliminary financial reports during the electoral period and a final and consolidated report after the election.</td><td class="d" id="d_154676">Yes</td><td>Candidates have also to submit monthly preliminary financial reports during the electoral period, through an automated system created by the EMB, and a final and consolidated report 60 days after the election.</td><td class="d" id="d_165041">No</td><td>However, the authority regularly publishes the list of those who submitted their financial reports, and citizens using their constitutional right may request the information. </td><td class="d" id="d_154678">Yes</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_163114">EMB</td><td>Through an automated system set up by the EMB itself in its webpage.</td><td class="d" id="d_159257">Yes, EMB</td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_159258"># Auditing agency<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /># Other<br style="mso-data-placement:same-cell" /></td><td></td><td class="d" id="d_154684">Fines</td><td>In case of infringement to Political finance provisions, EMB is entitled to impose fines that may range from 5,ooo to 7,000 tax units. </td></tr></tbody></table></body></html> 